There is no junit-specific facility to empower your idea. 

Unless you use *@TestInstance(Lifecycle.PER_CLASS)*, new instance of a test class will be created for each test call. That means, @Bill K is right, and you are welcome to initialize a test class field.

But the better way is to use [parametrized test](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.5.2/user-guide/#writing-tests-parameterized-tests) with [@MethodSource](https://junit.org/junit5/docs/5.5.2/user-guide/#writing-tests-parameterized-tests-sources-MethodSource) and performing *setup* right in the test somewhere in the _given_ section. This is precisely the task @ParametrizedTests are intended to solve.

    @TestInstance(TestInstance.Lifecycle.PER_CLASS)
    class TestSample {

       @ParameterizedTest
       @MethodSource(&quot;bars&quot;)
       fun isFive(bar:Int){
           setupSomethingWithBar(bar)  
           assertEquals(bar, 5)
       }

       fun bars() = (1..10).asSequence().asStream()
    }

