&gt; my Composite Aggregate has to implement Visitor

First question coming in my mind is, why?
Can&#39;t you declare the visitor as an interface, and pass the implementation as an input parameter of your aggregate?

&gt; Is there a way to simulate dynamic binding in java for overloaded methods (other than instanceof - since this would solve my problem with option 1)?  

Yes, you can do it using Reflections, but the real question is, do you want to use them?

I think the answer depends on how many cases you have to manage and how often they change?

If you have a &quot;manageable&quot; number of different cases a solution with the `instanceof` can be a good trade of:
```
public Something myMethod(Entity entity){
    if (entity instanceof AnEntity){
         //do stuffs
    else if (entity instanceof AnotherEntity){
         //do something else
    ...
    else {
         throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Not managed &quot; + entity.getClass().getName());
    }
}
```
Otherwise when maybe you have more cases and want to split the code in their own methods, you can do it using Java `MethodHandle`, let me post an example of usage:
```
package virtualmethods;

import java.lang.invoke.MethodHandles;
import java.lang.invoke.MethodType;

public class MyObject {

    public String doStuffs(Object i) throws Throwable {
        try {
            final MethodType type = MethodType.methodType(String.class, i.getClass());
            return (String) MethodHandles.lookup()
                .findVirtual(getClass(), &quot;doStuffs&quot;, type)
                .invoke(this, i);
        } catch (NoSuchMethodException e) {
            throw new RuntimeException(&quot;Not managed &quot; + i.getClass().getName(), e);
        }
    }

    private String doStuffs(Integer i) {
        return &quot;You choose &quot; + i;
    }
    private String doStuffs(Boolean b) {
        return &quot;You choose boolean &quot; + b;
    }
}
```
and then use it:
```
package virtualmethods;

public class Main {

    public static void main(String[] args) throws Throwable {

        MyObject object = new MyObject();

        System.out.println(&quot;Integer =&gt; &quot; + object.doStuffs(5));
        System.out.println(&quot;Boolean =&gt; &quot; + object.doStuffs(true));
        try {
            System.out.println(&quot;String =&gt; &quot; + object.doStuffs(&quot;something&quot;));
        }
        catch (Throwable e) {
            System.out.println(&quot;KABOOM&quot;);
            e.printStackTrace();
        }
    }

}
```
The *public* method in `MyObject` taking an `Object` will look for a method named `doStuffs` with a `String` result and an `i.getClass()` as input in class `MyObject` (more info [here](https://www.baeldung.com/java-method-handles)).  
Using this way you can dispatch methods at runtime (using overload is static linking at compile time).
But both methods has the problem that you can&#39;t be sure you will manage ALL the types that extends/implements `Entity` in the first case and/or `Object` in the second one, both solutions have an `else` or a `catch` to check when a not managed type is passed to the method.  
Be 100% sure you are managing all the types can be only achieved using the solution proposed by @jaco0646, for what I know, it force you to manage all the types, otherwise it won&#39;t compile.
